ons per advisor step 5.\n\n7. **Create auth guard middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/requireAuth.ts`\n   - Change: Export a middleware function that checks `req.session.userId`; if absent, returns 401. Mount this middleware on all protected route groups.\n   - Rationale: Wires auth enforcement before route handlers per advisor step 5.\n\n8. **Verify same-site posture and add CSRF if needed**\n   - File: `src/middleware/csrf.ts` (conditional)\n   - Change: If the frontend is on a different origin than the API (cross-site), implement double-submit CSRF tokens: generate a per-session token, set it in a readable cookie (`SameSite=Strict`, not `HttpOnly`), require it in `X-CSRF-Token` header on state-changing routes (POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE).\n   - Rationale: `SameSite=Lax` protects same-site frontends automatically; cross-site deployments need the double-submit pattern per advisor step 4.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Opaque server-side sessions vs. JWT cookies**: Chosen per advisor guidance because server-side sessions support revocation (logout, forced expiry, account lockout). JWTs in cookies cannot be invalidated before expiry without a blocklist, which recreates server-side state anyway.\n- **`__Host-` cookie prefix**: Use `__Host-sid` when the API is served over HTTPS on a bare host (no subdomains needed for the cookie). Fall back to a plain name with `Secure` only if the prefix causes issues with the framework's cookie API.\n- **Session store choice**: Must be a shared, persistent store (not in-memory) so sessions survive API restarts and work across horizontally scaled instances. Redis is the most common choice; Postgres works if Redis is unavailable.\n- **Risk -- HTTPS assumption**: The `Secure` flag silently drops the cookie over HTTP, breaking auth in local development. Conditionally omit `secure: true` when `NODE_ENV !== 'production'` or configure a local HTTPS proxy.\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Step 1 (identify framework) must complete before steps 2-8 -- all 